{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"fields":{"slug":"/astro/jskycalc"},"id":"4e65504e-173c-556a-9b4b-a2cc7dce50b9","html":"<h1 align=\"center\">\n  JSkyCalc\n</h1>\n<p align=\"center\">A convinient, portable observing aid.</p>\n<p><a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/e76528b79e94dbee2a9421b66ca310a8/68cbc/jskycalc.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 44.02092675635277%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    ></span>\n    <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"jskycalc\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/e76528b79e94dbee2a9421b66ca310a8/b9e4f/jskycalc.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/e76528b79e94dbee2a9421b66ca310a8/cf440/jskycalc.png 148w,\n/static/e76528b79e94dbee2a9421b66ca310a8/d2d38/jskycalc.png 295w,\n/static/e76528b79e94dbee2a9421b66ca310a8/b9e4f/jskycalc.png 590w,\n/static/e76528b79e94dbee2a9421b66ca310a8/f9b6a/jskycalc.png 885w,\n/static/e76528b79e94dbee2a9421b66ca310a8/2d849/jskycalc.png 1180w,\n/static/e76528b79e94dbee2a9421b66ca310a8/68cbc/jskycalc.png 1338w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n      />\n  </span>\n  </a></p>\n<p>Skycalc expedites the \"time-and-the-sky\" calculations needed by observational astronomers.</p>\n<h3 id=\"install-and-setup\"><a href=\"#install-and-setup\" aria-label=\"install and setup permalink\" class=\"post-toc-anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Install and Setup</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Go to Oracle-Java website and download the <code class=\"language-text\">dk-8u121-macosx-x64.dmg</code> file.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Go to JSkyCalc website and download the executable tar file.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Use command <code class=\"language-text\">mkdir ~/JSkyCalc</code> to create an empty directory in your home directory and name it <code class=\"language-text\">JSkyCalc</code>. Then, move executable tar file <code class=\"language-text\">JSkyCalc.jar</code> into this directory.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Use command jar -xvf JSkyCalc.jar from within ~/JSkyCalc directory to unpack jar file.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Edit skycalcsites.dat to add Mount Laguna Observatory as the first site (above Kitt Peak)--it will become the default. You may have to comment out an observatory to make room.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"ascii\"><pre class=\"language-ascii\"><code class=\"language-ascii\">&quot;Mount Laguna Obs.&quot;, 7.76173, 32.84, 8., 1, &quot;Pacific&quot;, &quot;P&quot;, 1859., 1859.</code></pre></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Add following lines to your <code class=\"language-text\">~/.bash_profile</code> file:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"vim\"><pre class=\"language-vim\"><code class=\"language-vim\"># use jsky command <span class=\"token keyword\">in</span> any <span class=\"token builtin\">directory</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">to</span> start JSkyCalc\nalias jsky<span class=\"token operator\">=</span><span class=\"token string\">'java JSkyCalc'</span>\nCLASSPATH<span class=\"token operator\">=</span>$CLASSPATH<span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>~<span class=\"token operator\">/</span>JSkyCalc\nexport CLASSPATH</code></pre></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Finally, use the command <code class=\"language-text\">source ~/.bash_profile</code> to source the file and then use jsky command to start using JSkyCalc from any directory! </p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>The following line is the general format for JSkyCalc (.dat) files:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">Name_no_blanks hh mm ss dd mm ss equinox +++</code></pre></div>\n<p>It's fine if all your stars have equinox=2000. Here is an example of <code class=\"language-text\">observe-star.dat</code> formatted for JSkyCalc.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">some_star 00 37 52.92 -09 42 16.5 2000.0 +++</code></pre></div>\n</li>\n</ol>","frontmatter":{"date":null,"title":"JSkyCalc","root":"/astro"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false}}